</div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" data-sqsp-block="text" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1564469134334_45063"><div class="sqs-block-content">

<div class="sqs-html-content" data-sqsp-text-block-content>
  <p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Changed hostels because my old one was still deserted, and made a new friend ‚ÄòB‚Äô in the lobby within ten minutes of walking in. Functionally, the place has worse rooms and location but it‚Äôs honestly worth the ambiance and social aspect of the common area.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">B is doing her master‚Äôs in conservation science and biology and does research on snakes, with a goal of destigmatizing the fear and bias (starting from Adam and Eve) we have against them. She‚Äôs been in Thailand to observe the biomes here and spent some time at a forest monastery for her program. It was invigorating to discuss the intersection between Buddhism and conservation efforts, given we‚Äôre both in the process of learning about the practice and I haven‚Äôt had to opportunity to discuss it with anyone thus far. Apparently she and her peers had an inquiry about how long leeches would stay on, and how big they could get, and ended up testing on themselves. Her‚Äôs was on for two hours...the things you do for science.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">We went up to a mountainside temple and hiked a few trails around the area. It was fun to have her point out random plants and giant bugs I wouldn‚Äôt have noticed on my own and share science trivia.&nbsp;</p>
</div>






















